      {
        "id": 4043824,
        "name": null,
        "username": "chetkern",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/c/d07c76/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2023-04-01T11:33:11.681Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I don\u2019t think that there exists a ceiling for anything all things wine that would prevent this incredibly passionate and extraordinarily intelligent young man from achieving.<br>\nThank you Greg K for arranging and bringing me along with you and our group to taste with and for me to personally meet William.  THE WINES WERE BOTTLED A FEW DAYS PRIOR.<br>\nI\u2019ve corresponded with William  on IG about white burgundy for a few years and was very pleased to meet him in person and at his cellar in Pommard, the former Domaine Mussy.<br>\nWilliam needs zero introduction but suffice it to say he is beyond what his written words convey and he is already an accomplished one man show wine maker and a devoted family man etc.</p>\n<p>His old vine Bourgogne Aligote spent 17 months maturing in barrel and is absolutely stunning, With the ripeness now being able to be achieved in the new Burgundy this is the anti Aligote that removed enamel from one\u2019s teeth years ago and begged for cassis.  This is rich, round, fresh as can be with lively balancing acidity and drinks like profound Chardonnay, Turned my head around about the heights Aligote can reach !</p>\n<p>The gentle 21 Chambolle Musigny is precise, balanced, light on its feet, with generous red fruit, and holds a surprise in reserve for those able to keep their hands off of this wonderful drink!  21 reds around both Cotes have surprised both vignerons and will same for those lucky enough to secure bottles of this pitifully small amounts of wine from this old school tiny vintage.</p>\n<p>The Gevrey Chambertin from a vineyard whose name I don\u2019t recall as I don\u2019t write my notes down, is predictably bigger but no less finessed than the Chambolle.  It drinks so well once again with a touch more acidity and a bit deeper and a bit darker fruit profile.  It wouldn\u2019t last long in my cellar, though can effortlessly age and improve for 7-10 years in my humble opinion.</p>\n<p>The Beaune ier cru from a vineyard that the late and great Terry Leighton from Kalin Cellars worked and bottled ( I forget the name of the vineyard ), is a different animal with much more of everything including power fruit and amplitude yet maintains impeccable balance.  This is one to follow over many years.</p>\n<p>I was left shaking my head as these wines had just been bottled and typically the bottling process makes the wines difficult to taste and requires the bottles time to recover from the shock of bottling but not any of these.</p>\n<p>For the record, 21 is an old school vintage, with light colors and lower alcohol than has been seen in years in burgundy and if you liked the 01\u2019s with a touch of 02 ripeness you\u2019ll love these wines.</p>\n<p>Bravo William and very pleased to meet you in person.</p>",
