      {
        "id": 4043858,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2023-04-01T13:13:21.314Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Thanks, Chet, for this very kind write up! Was a pleasure to meet you, too.</p>\n<p>The extremely gentle barrel-by-barrel hand bottling and an \u00e9levage that is managed with a view to keeping total sulfites low vs free sulfites (20-25 ppm free with only around 40-45 total) at bottling contribute to the wines hopefully not shutting down too hard.</p>\n<p>The Gevrey is from Aux Etelois, from the first 15 or so meters of a parcel that\u2019s right below the Griotte-Chambertin of Fourrier and Roty.</p>\n<p>The Beaune 1er Cru is Les Chouacheaux, a lesser-known 1er cru below the Vignes Franches and Clos des Ursules, and next to the Clos Saint-Landry of Bouchard, with David Croix\u2019s Pointe de Tulivans (in AOC Beaune) right below. David and I have both planted fruit trees in our parcels so the neighborhood is looking good!</p>\n<p>Oh, and the Aligot\u00e9 was actually a barrel sample! It will have a full 23-24 months on the lees before bottling.</p>",
